tools_called.args:
{"query": "How does the evidence for using shelterwood harvesting compare with clearcutting for promoting plant diversity and tree regeneration?", "summary": "Evidence from studies comparing shelterwood harvesting to clearcutting shows several differences regarding plant diversity and tree regeneration. Three replicated, controlled studies in Sweden and the USA found that shelterwood harvesting resulted in higher plant diversity, lower grass cover and higher density of tree species compared with clearcutting (Action 1214). Six of seven studies in Australia, Iran, Nepal and the USA found that shelterwood harvesting increased abundance, species richness and diversity of understory plants, as well as the growth and survival rate of young trees, while one study found it decreased plant species richness and abundance (Action 1223).

For clearcutting effects on plant diversity, eight of 12 studies in Belgium, Brazil, Canada, China, Germany, Israel, Spain and the USA found that clearcutting increased the cover and species richness of understory plants, though two found it decreased density and species richness (Action 1222). Three of six studies found that clearcutting increased the density and species richness of young trees, while one found it decreased new tree density (Action 1222).

When examining moth species richness recovery rates, one study found that moth species richness recovered faster after shelterwood harvesting than after group selection harvesting or clearcutting (Action 3871). One study found that group-selection harvesting increased cover and diversity of understory plants and the density of young trees, while recovery after management by group selection harvesting or clearcutting was similar but slower than after shelterwood harvesting (Actions 1224, 3868).", "action_ids": ["1214","1223","1222","3871","1224","3868"]}

